english:
  title: Memorial to Decline the Position of Chancellor
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your humble servant Geun respectfully submits: In the records of the Song Dynasty officials' memorials, Volume Thirty-Five, there is an account of Imperial Censor Zhong Fu Yaoyu's letter to Emperor Zhezong. The essence of it reads: "I have observed that Han Zhongyan served as Minister of the Left, and furthermore his younger brother Jiayen married into the imperial family. Widespread criticism arose, and many deemed this improper. Your servant believes that Li Deyu, truly a great minister of Tang, once established ancient precedent forbidding the Imperial Son-in-Law and high officials from associating with one another. Such were the safeguards of that era. Yet now all these connections converge in a single household. The words of those who discuss this matter are surely worthy of consideration." The Grand Remonstrator Fan Zuyu submitted a memorial stating: "Han Jiayen has been appointed Imperial Son-in-Law, while his elder brother Zhongyan holds executive power. Since the time of our ancestors, there has been no such precedent. How can we allow relatives by marriage to participate in governance from this day forward? I request that Zhongyan be stripped of his position, to serve as a lesson for posterity."

    When a younger brother becomes an Imperial Son-in-Law and an elder brother wields the power of state, even the ancients deemed this unseemly. How much more so when father and son have received excessive imperial favor—when my son has been honored through marriage to a princess, and I myself occupy the council of ministers, receiving honors beyond measure? This weighs heavily upon my conscience. Furthermore, my health has long been frail. My senses have dimmed, my mind clouds when attending to matters, and my faculties of observation have failed. Though I strive in service, I fear I am unfit. Since the sixteenth of this month, my ailment has resurged—food brings nausea, weakness overwhelms me. I lie upon my sickbed, groaning without respite. I humbly beseech Your Majesty to take pity upon this aging, ailing servant. Grant me release from office, that the precedent of those wise Song officials might guide your reign. Allow this old minister to find peace, to tend to his illness, and to preserve what remaining years heaven may grant. I would count myself most blessed.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Han Zhongyan and his brother Jiayen were historical figures from Northern Song whose family connections to imperial power sparked controversy about nepotism in governance. Gwon Geun invokes their example to justify his own request for resignation, as his son had married into the Korean royal family while Gwon himself served in high office.
  - key: ''
    value: Li Deyu (787-849) was a renowned Tang Dynasty chancellor known for maintaining strict separation between imperial family affairs and government administration—a policy Gwon Geun presents as a model for proper governance.
